Question : how to setup a dummy ui for junit test 4\
Answer:
"To set up a dummy UI for use in JUnit 4 tests, especially if you're testing classes that rely on a UI interface (like UI ui;), you can use an anonymous class or a mock to implement a minimal version of that UI. Here's how:

 ‚úÖ Option 1: Using Anonymous Class (Simple Dummy)
 If UI is an interface with methods like log(String msg) or displayMessage(String msg), create a minimal inline dummy:

 java
 Copy
 Edit
 UI dummyUI = new UI() {
     @Override
     public void log(String message) {
         // Do nothing or print for debug
         System.out.println("Log: " + message);
     }

     @Override
     public void displayMessage(String message) {
         // Optional: simulate output
     }

     // Implement other methods if needed
 };
 Then pass it to your class under test:

 java
 Copy
 Edit
 GameController controller = new GameController(dummyUI, achievementManager);
 ‚úÖ Option 2: Using Mockito (if allowed in your course/project)
 If you can use Mockito, it‚Äôs even easier:

 java
 Copy
 Edit
 import static org.mockito.Mockito.*;

 UI mockUI = mock(UI.class);
 GameController controller = new GameController(mockUI, achievementManager);
 You can also verify interactions:

 java
 Copy
 Edit
 verify(mockUI).log("Achievement Mastered: First Blood");
 ‚úÖ Example JUnit 4 Test with Dummy UI
 java
 Copy
 Edit
 public class GameControllerTest {

     private GameController controller;

     @Before
     public void setUp() {
         UI dummyUI = new UI() {
             @Override
             public void log(String message) {
                 // Optional: Collect logs for assertions
             }

             @Override
             public void displayMessage(String message) {
                 // Stub
             }

             // Add other methods if required by interface
         };

         AchievementManager dummyManager = new AchievementManager(new FileHandler());
         controller = new GameController(dummyUI, dummyManager);
     }

     @Test
     public void testStartGameInitialisesProperly() {
         controller.startGame();
         // Assertions here
     }
 }
 Let me know if your UI interface or class has specific methods, and I can generate a ready-to-use dummy with only those."